Halo{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f3\/Improve-Your-Gaming-Skills-Step-2Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Improve-Your-Gaming-Skills-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/f\/f3\/Improve-Your-Gaming-Skills-Step-2Bullet3.jpg\/aid1588386-v4-728px-Improve-Your-Gaming-Skills-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"} Get familiar with the controls. How do you shoot? How do you crouch? How do you jump? How do you pause the game? You can find the controls online or in the guide that comes with the video game. You can also customise your controls in most games. After you know all of the controls, practice each of them and make sure you can execute them with ease and quickly. Practice. As the saying goes, practice makes perfect. How are you supposed to improve your gaming skills if you don't even play video games that often? Acquire cheat codes, tricks, and shortcuts. These can be extremely helpful, especially when you're competing against someone. Knowing shortcuts or tricks gives you an edge. You can easily find out some online. Watch and compete against other gamers. By watching them, you can learn tricks and shortcuts or something you didn't know before. Competing with them can help you see what you need to improve on and what you're getting better at. Watch replays of your self playing. Review every step you take, what you were thinking at that moment. Compare your idea of what was happening and what was actually happening. Extremely helpful when playing games like shooters, strategy and racing games.
